### [**Dalip Singh (D) vs Sawan Singh (D) Through 2025 INSC 1498 \- TP Act \-Usufructuary mortgage \- Limitation**](https://www.caseciter.com/content/files/2025/12/Dalip-Singh--D--vs-Sawan-Singh--D--Through--2025-INSC-1498---TP-Act--Usufructuary-mortgage---Limitation.pdf)

**Transfer of Property Act 1882 \- Usufructuary mortgage** \- When there is a usufructuary mortgage, the period of limitation does not run from the date of creation of the mortgage but from the date of payment of mortgage- either out of the usufructuary or partly out of the usufructuary or partly on payment of deposit by mortgager as provided under Section 52 of Transfer of Property Act, 1882\. Till then the period of limitation would not start under Section 61 (a) of the Schedule to the Limitation Act. As such mere expiry of the period prescribed thereunder could not extinguish the mortgager’s right of redemption and thereby the right of mortgagee to seek declaration of title and ownership over the mortgage property stands untouched.\[Referred to Singh Ram (D) Vs. Sheo Ram (2014) 9 SCC 185 \] (Para 9\) 

